# Catering Server

Node.js/Express REST API for a catering service. MongoDB persistence, JWT auth, role-based access (admin/customer).

**Stack:** Express.js | MongoDB + Mongoose | JWT | Joi validation | Helmet

## Commands & Environment

```bash
npm install && npm run dev   # default PORT 3000
npm test                     # placeholder ‚Äî add tests as needed
```

Required `.env` variables:

- `MONGODB_URI` ‚Äî default `mongodb://localhost:27017/catering`
- `PORT` ‚Äî default `3000`
- `JWT_SECRET` ‚Äî JWT signing secret
- `NODE_ENV` ‚Äî `development` or `production`

## Architecture

```
src/
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ config/        # DB and service config
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ controllers/   # Thin HTTP handlers ‚Üí delegate to services
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ middlewares/   # auth, validation, error handling
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ models/        # Mongoose schemas (User, Dish, Package)
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ routes/        # Route definitions by feature
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ services/      # Business logic
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ utils/         # responseHandler, token helpers
‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ validations/   # Joi schemas
```

**Request flow:** Route ‚Üí Middleware (validation, auth) ‚Üí Controller ‚Üí Service ‚Üí Model

Each feature (auth, dishes, packages) follows: `routes/` ‚Üí `controllers/` ‚Üí `services/` ‚Üí `models/` + `validations/`

## Development Patterns

### Response handling

Always use `responseHandler`:

```javascript
const responseHandler = require('../utils/responseHandler');
responseHandler.success(res, data, message, statusCode);
responseHandler.error(res, message, statusCode);
```

### Validation

- Joi schemas in `validations/`
- Apply via `validate(schema, 'body')` middleware before controller

### Authentication

- Protected routes: `verifyToken` middleware ‚Üí sets `req.user.id`
- Admin routes: add `isAdmin` middleware

### Error handling

- Services throw descriptive errors
- Controllers map to HTTP status (401, 404, 409, 500)
- Global error handler catches unexpected errors

## Adding a Feature

1. Model ‚Üí `models/FeatureName.js`
2. Validation ‚Üí `validations/feature.validation.js`
3. Service ‚Üí `services/feature.service.js` (all business logic here)
4. Controller ‚Üí `controllers/feature.controller.js` (thin ‚Äî no duplicated logic)
5. Routes ‚Üí `routes/feature.routes.js`
6. Mount in `app.js`: `app.use('/api/feature', require('./src/routes/feature.routes'))`

## Adding an Endpoint

1. Add Joi schema to validation file
2. Implement service method (Mongoose queries live in services only)
3. Add controller method
4. Wire route with validation + auth middleware as needed

## API Endpoints

| Route | Methods |
|-------|---------|
| `/api/auth` | `POST /register`, `POST /login`, `GET /profile` (auth) |
| `/api/dishes` | Full CRUD |
| `/api/packages` | Full CRUD |
